Abt 1194":"about 1194","1214":"1214","1203":"1203","1200":"1200","Murom, Vladimir, Russia, U.S.S.R.":"Murom, Vladimir Oblast, Russia, Soviet Union","murom, Vladimirskaya Oblast', Rússia":"murom, Vladimir Oblast, Russia","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Murom","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Manuel, Jose, Jesus, Juan, Miguel, Alejandro, Arturo, Francisco, Luis, Ruben, Margarita, Alfonso.  Portuguese Armanda.  Italian Antonio, Angelo, Pasquale, Rocco, Salvatore, Carmelo, Carmine, Cira, Filomena, Heriberto, Luigi, Mirella.","Spanish and Italian: habitational name from any of various places in Spain and Italy named Muro, from <i>muro</i> ‘wall’. Compare Spanish   Del Muro   and Italian   De Muro  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Del Muro","meanings":["Spanish: variant, with the preposition and definite article <i>del</i> ‘from the’, of   Muro  . This surname is very rare in Spain; it is found mainly in Mexico."]}]},{"name":"Yurij","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The usual Russian form of   George  , also used occasionally in the English-speaking world."],"variants":[{"name":"George","meanings":["Via Old French and Latin, from Greek <i>Georgios</i> (a derivative of <i>geōrgos</i> ‘farmer’, from <i>gē</i> ‘earth’ + <i>ergein</i> ‘to work’). This was the name of several early saints, including the shadowy figure who is now the patron of England (as well as of Germany and Portugal). If the saint existed at all, he was perhaps martyred in Palestine in the persecutions of Christians instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  at the beginning of the 4th century. The popular legend in which the hero slays a dragon is a medieval Italian invention. He was for a long time a more important saint in the Orthodox Church than in the West, and the name was not much used in England during the Middle Ages, even after  St George  came to be regarded as the patron of England in the 14th century. Its use increased from the 1400s, and by  1500  it was regularly among the most popular male names. This popularity was reinforced when  George I  came to the throne in  1714 , bringing this name with him from Germany. It has been one of the most popular English boys' names ever since."]},{"name":"Georgi","meanings":["From Greek <i>Georgios</i>.  See  <b>George</b>   ."]}]},{"name":"Davidovich","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Rina, Avi, Izya, Mendel, Rifka, Rivka, Tuvia.  Russian Boris, Svetlana, Arkadiy, Ayzik, Fima, Losif, Yuriy.","Ukrainian (standard transliteration <b>Davydovych</b>), Belorussian, and Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): patronymic from the personal name   David   (Ukrainian <i>Davyd</i>).","Americanized form of Serbian and Croatian <b>Davidović</b>, a cognate of 1 above."],"variants":[{"name":"David","meanings":["Biblical name, borne by the greatest of all the kings of Israel, whose history is recounted with great vividness in the first and second books of Samuel and elsewhere. As a boy he killed the giant Philistine Goliath with his slingshot. As king of Judah, and later of all Israel, he expanded the power of the Israelites and established the security of their kingdom. He was also noted as a poet, many of the Psalms being attributed to him. The Hebrew derivation of the name is uncertain; it is said by some to represent a nursery word meaning ‘darling’. It is a very popular Jewish name, but is almost equally common among Gentiles in the English-speaking world. It is particularly common in Wales and Scotland, having been borne by the patron saint of Wales (  see  Dewi   ) and by two medieval kings of Scotland."]}]},{"name":"Duke","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["In modern use this normally represents a coinage parallel to   Earl   and   King  , but it has been used as a short form of   Marmaduke   from at least the early 1600s."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Yurij Davidovich Duke Murom was born about 1194, in murom, Vladimir Oblast, Russia, his father, David Petr Yurevich, was 26 and his mother, Fevroniya Evrosiniya, was 22. He married Mrs- Yurij Davidovich Duchess Of Murom about 1213, in murom, Vladimir Oblast, Russia. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in December 1237, at the age of 44."},"et":{"Abt 1194–   Dec 1237":"umbes 1194–detsember 1237","1194–1237":"1194–1237","1196–1228":"1196–1228","1198–1228":"1198–1228","1200–Male":"1200–Surnud","1203–Female":"1203–Surnud","1196–Female":"1196–Surnud","1214–1248":"1214–1248","1170–1228":"1170–1228","1174–Female":"1174–Surnud","   Dec 1237":"detsember 1237","1198":"1198","Abt 1214":"umbes 1214","1174":"1174","1196":"1196","Abt 1213":"umbes 1213","Apr 1228":"aprill 1228","1194":"1194","1193":"1193","1170":"1170","1228":"1228","1248":"1248","1237":"1237","Abt 1194":"umbes 1194","1214":"1214","1203":"1203","1200":"1200","Murom, Vladimir, Russia, U.S.S.R.":"Murom, Vladimirskaya Oblast', Russia, Nõukogude Liit","murom, Vladimirskaya Oblast', Rússia":"murom, Vladimirskaya Oblast', Venemaa"},"fi":{"Abt 1194–   Dec 1237":"noin 1194–joulukuu 1237","1194–1237":"1194–1237","1196–1228":"1196–1228","1198–1228":"1198–1228","1200–Male":"1200–Kuollut","1203–Female":"1203–Kuollut","1196–Female":"1196–Kuollut","1214–1248":"1214–1248","1170–1228":"1170–1228","1174–Female":"1174–Kuollut","   Dec 1237":"joulukuu 1237","1198":"1198","Abt 1214":"noin 1214","1174":"1174","1196":"1196","Abt 1213":"noin 1213","Apr 1228":"huhtikuu 1228","1194":"1194","1193":"1193","1170":"1170","1228":"1228","1248":"1248","1237":"1237","Abt 1194":"noin 1194","1214":"1214","1203":"1203","1200":"1200","Murom, Vladimir, Russia, U.S.S.R.":"Murom, Vladimirskaya Oblast', Russia, Sowjetunion","murom, Vladimi